   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <persName>
                  <name key="Virius" type="cognomen">
                     <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Vi</supplied>ri</name>
               </persName>
               <lb n="2"/>
               <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">v</supplied>
               <unclear>i</unclear>vas!
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Virius, may you live!</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Transcription from Richter (1956 [1920]), who herself follows the suggestions of Miss. Guarducci. The first line ends with "i" which may suggests the vocative of a name ends with "ius," if so we should supply either "Vi" for "Veirius" (as here) oe "Fu" for "Furius." In the 1920 edition of the catalog, Richter notes he style of the portraits is that of the 3rd c. CE. In the 1956 she adds that, following Mrs. Calza, the portraits may be of Helena and Constantine the Great (306-337 CE), which dates the gem to the first half of the fourth century CE. </p>
         </div>
